display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> be a <fr:link
type="local"
href="ring-0001.xml"
addr="ring-0001"
title="Ring">Ring</fr:link>. The <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Center</html:dfn> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> is the subring <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[Z(R)]]></fr:tex> consisting of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[z\in  R]]></fr:tex> such that for all <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[r\in  R]]></fr:tex> we have <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[zr=rz]]></fr:tex> and also (for non-associative rings) for all <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[r,s\in  R]]></fr:tex> and for all <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[z\in  Z(R)]]></fr:tex> we have <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[z(rs)=(zr)s]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[r(zs)=(rz)s]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(rs)z=r(sz)]]></fr:tex>. In other words, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[Z(R)]]></fr:tex> consists of elements which commute and associate with all elements of the ring.</fr:p>
 
   
