title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p><fr:strong>Uniqueness:</fr:strong> If there are two possible centers, it's obvious they contain the same elements, which means they are equal to each other.</fr:p>
<fr:p><fr:strong>Existence:</fr:strong> We see that the underlying set is nonempty and well-defined. We just need to show it is closed under addition and multiplication and contains <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[0\in  Z(R)]]></fr:tex>...well, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[0r=0=r0]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[r\in  R]]></fr:tex>, so <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[0\in  Z(R)]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
<fr:p>We see for any <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[z,w\in  Z(R)]]></fr:tex> that for all <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[r\in  R]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(z+w)r=zr+wr=rz+rw=r(z+w)]]></fr:tex> which means <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[z+w\in  Z(R)]]></fr:tex>. So it's closed under addition</fr:p>
<fr:p>We see for any <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[z,w\in  Z(R)]]></fr:tex> that for all <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[r\in  R]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(zw)r=z(wr)=(wr)z=(rw)z=r(wz)=r(zw)]]></fr:tex> which means <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[zw\in  Z(R)]]></fr:tex>. So it's closed under multiplication.</fr:p>
<fr:p>Taken together, this means there exists a well-defined center <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[Z(R)]]></fr:tex> which is a subring of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p><html:span
